content.description: On the day the Spanish fast-fashion chain opened its first store in the city (two weeks after one opened in Delhi), Lower Parel’s Phoenix Mills was infiltrated by a swarm of mallrats carrying Zara’s brown paper bag. Inside the plush two-level, 1,500 sq meter store, it was a bit of a circus. Frenzied shoppers lugged around armfuls of loot. Some patiently waited their turn at the changing room, others added to the chaos at the payment counters, where long queues meant waiting for 30 minutes to an hour. The brouhaha over the opening even spread to the streets of Colaba, where street vendors wooed shoppers by yelling, “Yeh Zara ka hai.”A high-street favourite, Zara is known for filtering down runway trends to the masses. The racks here have everything from printed leotards and striped shirts to electric stilettos and Lady Gaga T-shirts. We found that Zara’s trend-led fashion accommodates Indian sizes and stocks roughly the same merchandise as its international outposts.Zara in India is by no means the budget-shopper’s paradise, in contrast to its positioning worldwide. That said, its collection of summery dresses (Rs 2,100), charcoal print T-shirts (Rs 800) and ripped jeans (Rs 2,100 each) don’t burn as big a hole in the pocket as its designer neighbour Burberry. In fact, it is one of the few shops in the Palladium where you can walk past the massive display windows, browse and pick an outfit without getting the “May I help you” from a salesperson, a polite euphemism for “What are you doing here?” While the store stocks trendy wear for toddlers as well as dandies, the women’s section is the strongest. The ground floor stocks charming partywear, breezy dresses, linen pants and skirts and painfully gorgeous stilettos, all available in pastel shades. The first level is dedicated to younger buyers, with Zara’s lowest-priced brand TRF, which stocks beachy must-haves and crisp, broderie-anglaise dresses that deserve a second look. The men’s collection covers frayed jeans, twill trousers, loafers in buttery leather, hats and cufflinks and has enough for men to go gaga over. Zara claims to change its stock every two weeks and we visited two weeks later to check. There were many new inviting additions at the store. However, the printed dress we had been eyeing and saving for had disappeared.We liked: The pricing, which matches that of the ubiquitous Bandra boutiques selling first copies of Zara from Bangkok. We didn’t like: The “Made for India” exclusive rack, which stocked fuchsia accessories that failed to dazzle.

Ornamental Buddhist gongs fringed with ostrich feathers glow from the ceiling of the newly-opened Snip Salon and Spa, the Mumbai outlet of Sumeet and Archana Bhobe’s Goa chain. There were more feathers in my treatment room, along the edge of the light installation. They fluttered at me like friendly tarantulas, but did not ruffle the serene ambience.The menu lists Hungarian organic facials and detoxifying herbal mud packs, which come with complimentary back rubs. I opted for a new addition that didn’t include a rub: a “wild plum eye lift” that promised to soothe eyes stressed from contact lenses and computer screens. It is also featured in the age-reversal spa package for women. I also tried a foot reflexology treatment with peppermint and menthol cream that is included in a spa package for jet-lagged men. The staff at Snip Salon and Spa are warm and attentive. The therapist Son wiped my feet with a warm towel and another therapist Yanti gently cleansed my eyelids with a moist, fragrant tissue. Then began a dance of extremities as Son powerfully dug into the sorest points from my soles to my mid-thighs and Yanti’s lithe fingertips crisscrossed like butterflies across my eyelids and temples. Yanti used lotions from the organic brand Eminence, starting off with a cooling cucumber gel before laying on a raspberry mask, followed by a wild plum cream. Her fingertips pattered on my skin, traced the ridges of my eyes, brushed against my eyebrow line and lightly pressed at my temples. It seemed a bit extravagantly-priced, but the soothing treatment was a relief and a charming diversion from the pummeling my lower limbs were getting. Son said the Taiwanese technique employed in the foot reflexology treatment worked on the internal organs, circulatory and respiratory system. He located secret points of pain in my body, easing out the tension and knots locked in the calf muscles and under my knees. His fingers drummed against each of the tiny bones in my feet, raked down my heels and squeezed my toes to jelly, while slathering on a peppermint and menthol cream that made my skin tingle for hours. My now-awakened limbs were given a warm rub-down with a hot towel. Feeling loosened up after all that smoothening and kneading, I sipped on lemonade before emerging back on the city’s drizzly streets.

content.description: “First, observe the bowl,” the ancient noodle master instructs in a Yoda-like tone. “Savour the aromas. Look at the jewels of fat glittering on the surface. See the seaweed slowly sinking. Concentrate on the three slices of pork. Now, caress the surface with your chopsticks; express your affection.” His discourse lasts for four minutes but you’ll never look at a bowl of noodle soup the same way again. Tampopo, a Japanese comedy about two truck drivers and a fast-food restaurant, is filled with vignettes about the role food plays in our lives. There’s a yakuza gangster and his mistress who put raw egg yolk to racy uses, a Japanese etiquette class on how to eat spaghetti and an old woman intent on squeezing food. The scenes range from hilarious to heart warming but the one thing they have in common is that they’ll leave you hungry, even lusting, for more. Satisfy your craving at Asia 7. Skip the exotica and order a vast bowl of their broth-heavy barbecue chicken noodle soup and remember the ramen master’s words. Neha Sumitran

content.description: It’s a pity Cafe Cabana doesn’t serve alcohol. Only booze-induced creativity could have helped us make sense of the décor. The entrance is bathed in bright green light that’s more horror-house than beachside shelter. The interiors are equally shocking: bright red pool tables, electric blue walls and glow-in-the-dark swirls of smoke painted on them. A giant Native American-style totem head sits in the middle of the dining area. Luckily, some of the tables are tucked into booth-like enclosures that let you hide from the Big Chief’s gaze. The couches are comfortably low, designed to let you lean back and take deep long drags of a hookah.It was hard to tell whether the sweet smell was emerging from the hookahs or deodorant that the teenaged clients were wearing. Judging by the large groups of youngsters, the bikes parked outside and the music playing loudly on the music system, this place was fast becoming one of Mulund’s hippest joints.It’s clear from the menu where Cafe Cabana’s aspirations lie: in a certain hookah establishment in Churchgate that is famous for its coffee and conversations. There’s the usual mix of hot and cold coffees, pastas and pizzas. These days, which hookah bar menu could be complete without Maggi? We had to try the Maggi Arrabiata (Rs 109), for the comfort that only instant noodles can bring. The chef had used masala noodles, added some chopped tomatoes and black olives and seemed confident that there’s almost no way that Maggi noodles can go wrong. Not so the other forms of noodles, alas. The baked pasta with chicken (Rs 179) turned out to be so tasteless that we were glad it came with three gently toasted slices of garlic bread. The only other flavour came from the little kernels of corn that had been tossed in the white sauce with the macaroni elbows. The lemonade with orange and pink (Rs 80) looked and tasted just like sweet nimbu-paani. The cottage cheese salad (Rs 90) lacked any dressing, though the crunchy iceberg lettuce and perfectly-diced tomatoes, cucumbers, croutons and paneer were flavourful. After all that blandness, the Cabana special (Rs 180) seemed even more exciting than it really was. Strips of chicken, marinated in a Chinese-chilli sauce, are served with slivers of red and yellow capsicum and chopped green chillies. Even the chicken supreme pizza (Rs 159) was a surprising mix of sweet, sour and spicy flavours. Only two things were available from the dessert menu: chocolate mousse and chocolate brownie (Rs 99). We wished we had chosen the mousse, because the brownie turned out to be so hard, we needed a knife to cut it. Even chocolate sauce and vanilla ice couldn’t save this dessert disaster. We should have just followed the teenagers’ example. Stick to the starters, a soft drink and shoot some pool (Rs 80 for 30 minutes) while you bob your head to the latest hits by Rihanna. Aditya Kundalkar Cafe Cabana Near Fortis Hospital (formerly Wockhardt Hospital), Mulund-Goregaon Link Road, Mulund (W) (2562-4999).Daily 11am-midnight. All major credit cards. Meal for two approx Rs 400

content.short-description: Real estate eagles may have scavenged every last plot of land around Kamala Mills and turned them into swanky corporate parks.
content.description: A quickie at lunch.Real estate eagles may have scavenged every last plot of land around Kamala Mills and turned them into swanky corporate parks. But for those who have to spend work hours there, there’s a despair that even the shiny buildings cannot hide. Cabbies refuse to make the short trip to Phoenix Mills and with only half an hour for lunch, quick lunches are often available only by the roadside. Every afternoon, offices empty and the pavements fill up with executives lining up at vendors doling out express meals.Kshitij Morarkar, the man behind the counter at Mumbai Deli, wants to move this crowd indoors. His restaurant is smack in the middle of Jai Hind and Shree Krishna restaurants and both have their share of loyalists. Mumbai Deli fights back with a menu that offers what the neighbours don’t: basil-and-chive marinades, white wine vinaigrettes and chilled gazpacho. All this is without the fancy trappings that fancy grub usually brings. The Deli sticks to steel stools and tableware that consists of take-out boxes, even as their walls sport the Mumbai-themed photographs we’ve also seen at Woodside Inn. Their menu sticks to light basics like soups, salads, wraps and sandwiches. Our generous serving of the chicken, mushroom and leek soup (Rs 65) came without cream or butter. Its coarse texture came from pureed leeks and mushrooms; there were chunks of grilled chicken at the bottom and a mild dusting of pepper on top. Barley has never tasted as good as it did in the barley and zucchini salad (Rs 50).The pearly grains, glistening with lemon-garlic dressing, came with diced zucchini and bell peppers. Most of the food here is ready-to-go, so if you get a frantic work call mid-meal you can just pick up your container and get walking. Judging by the number of phone orders he received in the one hour we were there, Mumbai Deli seems to be pretty popular.Morarkar recommended the Italian spicy grilled panini (Rs 90) which came with a rosemary and oregano-flavoured tomato spread. The mildly tart spread and the basil-marinated mushroom balanced out the sweetness of the caramelised onion. But the herb-overkill left the sandwich with no distinct flavour. Curious to try the red wine vinaigrette, we ordered the basil and chive chicken sandwich (Rs 110). The herb-marinated chicken drizzled with the vinaigrette added zing to the meal. We think Lower Parel could do with more places like this. But if they want to keep us from hopping over to the jalebiwala outside, they’ll need to work on their desserts. Their cinnamon roll (Rs 50) evoked none of the warm, familiar feelings sweet baked goods should. Kainaz Contractor Mumbai Deli Next to Jai Hind Restaurant, Senapati Bapat Marg, Lower Parel (6529-3154/56). Mon-Sat 8am-8pm. Meal for two approx Rs 400. Cash only.

content.description: Beyond tooth.You may already know Kakori House’s takeaway outlet in Bandra, but what you may not know about Kakori is printed on the paper napkins that sit on the tables of its new sit-down outlet in Mahim. The napkins are as informative as they are absorbent, describing where Kakori is (near Lucknow) and what it’s famous for (a train robbery in 1925 by freedom fighters to fund the revolution) and, of course, the kebabs.Kakori kebabs are supposed to be so soft that they can be enjoyed even by toothless meat aficionados, like the Lucknawi nawab for whom they were allegedly invented. The meat has to be tenderised with raw papaya, flavoured with garam masala and cooked on a skewer in a tandoor.The kakori kebabs (Rs 160) we ordered were so tender that our waiter had to carefully slide each tube of meat from his platter to ours so that each slender cylinder would stay intact. They were so soft that we had no trouble talking with our mouths full. Each morsel filled the contours of the mouth with its delicate flavours and slid down the gullet, leaving behind in its wake a taste of the fragrant mix of spices. The subz galawati kebabs (Rs 110), because of their crisp-fried skin, seemed firmer at first but the crispiness could barely conceal the soft and spicy vegetable flesh, minced so fine that we couldn’t tell which vegetables had gone into it.Though the menu is just a takeaway pamphlet, it does describe each dish in one line so you don’t have to ask the waiter what murgh begum bahar means or what the nihari gosht is. Taken in by the description that said “tender juicy pieces of mutton simmered in its own juices”, we ordered nihari gosht (Rs 160) and whole wheat roomali rotis (Rs 20). The menu doesn’t have roomali rotis made with maida, perhaps because they’d be too soft to contain the limp tenderness of the meat. Though the warqi paratha (Rs 30) was made with maida, it was thick enough to support the mutton in the mildly-spiced nihari gosht, which was almost as supple as the kebabs. The gravy was lightly spiced, smooth and comforting like a thick broth.The dum murg masala biryani (Rs 170) is served boneless and by now we know why – they don’t want you to use your teeth unless absolutely necessary. Even the chunks of chicken in this biryani, although marinated and cooked really well, suddenly seemed too firm. As for taste, it wasn’t as delicate as a biryani ought to be, and spicy-sour flavours overpowered the saffron or clove, if there actually was any in it.For dessert, we had zaafrani malai phirni (Rs 65) and shahi tukda (Rs 75). The phirni wasn’t thickened with either cream or rice, but some other form of starch. It was, however, just sweet enough and sprinkled with plenty of sliced almonds and pistas. The shahi tukda behaved just like the kebabs, dissolving like a cloud of sweetness on the tongue. The spoonful of melted barfi with almond and pista slivers on top added a special touch.If you can avoid it, try not to look at the paintings on the wall. Each one borrowing from a progressively more ominous palette of red. The first one depicts the train robbery, the second highlights the freedom fighters’ spirit of revolution but the last one is particularly striking. A noose hangs in the centre of the canvas, stark white against the blood-red sky. It’s as if they don’t want you to forget the sacrifice of the convicted freedom fighters nor of the animals that were slaughtered to prepare the kebabs. Aditya Kundalkar

content.description: Indigo Café – unlike Indigo restaurant, Indigo Deli in Colaba and Tote – has an unimpressive location. However, Indigo Café wins with the un-snobby enthusiasm of its staff, who enthusiastically help you pick your poison and other tasty delights. The 16-table Café’s menu is an extended remix of Deli’s menu. So there are the familiar riffs of breakfast all day, sandwiches and burgers. But it has been layered with more appetisers and mains, and has ten options of their so-thin-it’s-translucent-crust pizzas (instead of Deli’s two). The pesto, tomato, mozzarella is so good, it’s hard to share. But save your appetite for the remarkably tender salt-rubbed chicken, criss-crossed with grill marks and served with red wine sauce. Save space for the croissant pudding with salty bourbon sauce and three chocolate mousse (dark chocolate, mocha, milk chocolate). Mood-altering alcohol, cocoa and sugar haven’t had a better medium

content.description: The modest, vegetarian Bellagio Bistro is not named after the Vegas casino that Danny Ocean’s posse ransacked in Ocean’s Eleven. They have nothing in common, except that both their names were inspired by the same North Italian district. So there are creamy risottos, gorgonzola pizzas, and buttery ravioli. To mix things up, we suppose, the owners have also thrown in some Lebanese, Indian, and Asian dishes. Their creamy three-grain risotto, made from Arborio, barley and wheat with parmesan and kalamata olives is a perfect bite. Their crunchy chocolate cake has all the makings of being the next big thing in party desserts. A coating of snappy dark chocolate and rice crisps gives way to the heady, ultra-moist dark cake centre

content.description: The Italian chain Casa Mia, much like its sole relative in the vicinity, Little Italy, claims to offer shoppers a homely experience. The restaurant, designed to look like a European sidewalk café, is uncluttered and welcoming, just as mamma would’ve liked it. That explains the menu, which offers trivia about ricotta bearing a resemblance to cottage cheese and Arborio rice getting its name from the town of its origin. A must-try is the misto italiano platter, a sampling of all their signature antipastis, including bruschetta, salads, cheese, fried calamari, cold cuts and olives. Keeping in mind the homely theme, the waiters cheerily flit from table to table offering a drizzle of olive oil and a sprinkling of pepper with chefs in the show kitchens smiling as they flung dough in the air. Don’t leave without digging into the tiramisu. The creamy mascarpone with coffee-soaked, crisp and sweet savoiardi lady-finger biscuits and a light dust of powdered cocoa plays touch-and-go with your taste buds

A great place for an unhurried, unlimited thali in Kala Ghoda, Chetana offers three kinds of Gujarati, Maharashtrian and Rajasthani vegetarian set meals every day including a health thali (possibly the city’s most vegan-friendly thali, cooked without oil, chilli and dairy products) and what they refer to as a Sattwik Thali (a tourist-friendly version with less oil and spice). Skip breakfast if you're heading there for lunch and walk home if you’re there for dinner

content.description: Swadshakti, probably the city’s only Ayurvedic restaurant is close to, yet far from, Malad’s bustle, off the Link Road, in the three-storied building that houses Ayushakti. A significant part of the menu is dedicated to panchakarma dishes, which exclude tomatoes, brinjal, ladies fingers, tamarind, curd and other fermented substances and all meat. In their thalis you’d find a number of rice-based dishes (rice noodles, khichdis, freshly ground rice dosas, rice pancakes topped with fruit). Apart from the healthy fare, pao bhaji shares space with sev puri, whole-wheat sandwiches with soups, and multi-grain parathas with tandoori dishes (tofu, soya and corn). Eating at Swadshakti will make you feel like you’ve erased the accumulated sins of years of bad eating

Shopping at Khadi Bhandar has always had less to do with satisfying retail cravings and more to do with national duty – Gandhi, after all, pioneered the idea of ethical consumption. Apart from bales of fabric and piles of ready-to-wear clothes in hand-spun khadi, the store used to stock eco-friendly cosmetics and leather products made from the skins of animals that had died naturally. Although the soaps and massage oils are still around, the store has discontinued its ahimsa or non-violent leather products. Stick with the clothing. There are plain and printed shirts and kurtas in cotton and silk. Men have better choices than women. The chief draw is the plain white khadi cotton shirts, available for under Rs 300. Also poke your head into the back of the capacious store for affordable table napkins (under Rs 40) and towels (under Rs 100)

content.description: Despite the wet weather, this Italian eatery fills up fast with patrons jumping to sample the saltimbocca – thin slices of veal topped with ham – which is Italian for “jump into the mouth” and the superlative starter of dates with gorgonzola and mozzarella. The outside section affords views of the bhelpuri stalls on Juhu beach and allows diners to feel smug and toasty as they watch others getting as soaked as Mandakini in Ram Teri Ganga Maili. The slatted windows and hanging plants and saffron alcoves with mirrors and pictures, all work in concert to make the place seem cosily inviting. The attention to detail, though, is best reflected in the food

content.description: In this two-storeyed store, locally produced organic crops share shelf space with imported low-calorie foods (on whose transportation more than a little carbon has been expended). But that’s carping. Mother Earth succeeds in making responsible buying more convenient – without costing the earth. The store sells a variety of products, such as funky cloth bags from Manipal, that are sourced from rural producers and Fair Trade companies. Their brightly hued cane bags are both functional and charming

content.description: Unlike other roof-top restaurants that shut shop during the monsoons, Dome manages to get away with a retractable roof, making sure their diners don’t get drenched while soaking in the beauty of Mumbai’s rains. This bar and grill occupies the hotel’s eighth-floor terrace and overlooks the whole glorious arc of the seafront promenade. The walls are white, the tiled floor is white and the abundant big sofas and armchairs are all covered in white cotton too. A raised platform holds the pool, while a corner rotunda houses a sleek aluminium-and-glass bar counter with matching stools. Even though it is more a bar than a restaurant, Dome serves food from both the InterContinental Marine Drive’s restaurants now, so you can pick from kebabs and cannelloni. We like that the cocktail menu sticks with the classics, so none of the Sex On The Beach nonsense, while the rest of the drinks list is catholic enough to embrace at one end a bottle of Dom Perignon and at the other a humble bottle of Kingfisher.

content.description: It may not be the most obvious way to save the earth, but it sure is the prettiest. Nihar Mehta’s curio cottage in Andheri stocks the Spreco collection of recycled home décor. With its sixties flower power-meet-Bollywood kitsch designs, the knick-knack collection (its name is Italian for waste) uses techniques like decoupage and collage to breathe new life into discarded junk. Among the array of sweet nothings are handpainted plastic Pepsi bottles (Rs 292) snipped to look like flower pots. Other bric-a-brac includes glass bottles painted and mix-matched with scraps of Bollywood pictures (Rs 452) as well as papier-mâché jewellery such as neckpieces and bracelets (Rs 752). For the Green conscious, there are Indigreen bags (Rs 3,552) and T-shirts (Rs 1,202), made of organic cotton that carry filmi harangues on environmental causes

With its warm, minimalist, aesthetic the KGC definitely looks the part of an artsy hangout. Even though the café has space constraints, the seating on the attic-like upper level solves this problem. It’s a conversation-friendly location, with polite staff and mouth-watering chocolate cake (as moist and fudgy as a brownie). But it could do with more food and lower prices. After all, upcoming artists and students (like the city’s journos) are a habitually poor and hungry lot. Still, when you’re sipping on your favourite cup of coffee and nibbling on a cookie underneath the skylight, a warm, fuzzy kind of feeling washes all over you

content.description: There’s never much incentive to step out on muggy, mucky rainy days. All anybody wants to do, especially on Sunday mornings, is laze around in bed for as long as possible. Salt Water Café is an exception. Waffles dripping with melted butter and luscious maple syrup, spare rib burgers with fruit chutney, and tuna pate and wasabi – their breakfast never disappoints.And should you stick around for lunch, give the usual suspects a miss and try out some of their more unusual combinations.This is how owner Riyaaz Amlani explained Salt Water Café’s menu: “We’ve tried to pair diametrically opposite flavours.” The result is a board of offerings that includes such intriguing dishes as truffle risotto with spiced chocolate oil, smoked duck carbonara and candied orange peel, and baked lamb chops with prune chutney. We’ve been back many times to work our way through the rest of the menu

content.description: Despite the fact that it’s located in a lane off noisy Juhu Tara Road, Vie exudes an aura of calm. Many elements combine to provide an ambience that’s airy and cool and a mood that’s soothing and relaxed. Stucco walls, whispering palms, candle-lit tables and a panoramic view of Juhu beach make Vie an ideal spot for a quiet bite and drink with friends or lovers. The service is efficient and the martinis are delicious. You’ll get the best value for money from the Italian-leaning Sunday brunch. We suggest getting a seat in the outdoor area, for Vie is an experience best enjoyed when playing hide-and-seek with the pouring rains

content.description: Thin-crust pizza, unhurried pints of beer and long, leisurely views of the strollers on Colaba Causeway. These are the primary attractions of Woodside Inn, the slightly dingy vegetarian restaurant and bar at the head of Wodehouse Road that’s undergone a remarkable transformation to emerge as an airy Mediterranean-focussed bistro. The management has also recently started breakfast, with all the old staples given a Woodside twist: waffles, pancakes and eggs. We think Mumbai could do with more places like this. In a fast-food city that’s increasingly gobbling up its nutrition on the trot, Woodside Inn is a gentle summon to fritter away rainy afternoons in a haze of conversation

content.description: Fancy a side of short films to go with your chai? Perhaps you like reading a book on filmmaking as you order some snacks. At Oshiwara’s Café Lalten, patrons can choose from a short film menu as well as the café menu and watch the film on a laptop as they nurse their cuppa. Apart from the usual cappuccino, it serves up much-loved local lovelies that don’t make it to swanky coffee shops: the masala chai in earthen cups and haldi milk. Instead of popcorn they have salads, sandwiches, wraps and even momos to complement your movie. It’s a bit like the cafés in Leh, where travellers can enjoy a cup of coffee while watching document-aries on Tibet. All they charge is a nominal viewing fee of Rs 20 per film, of which 40 per cent goes to the filmmaker. They also organise jam sessions and poetry readings to keep the buzz going in their modest café. There have been days when the café’s patrons have been out on the streets with cups in their hands. They weren’t protesting rising food costs. There just happened to be a huge turnout for an al fresco screening, forcing the crowds to spill over on to the streets. But with the chirpy yellow and green walls lined with red lanterns, the posters of ’60s Hollywood hits and a sizeable collection of short films on portable miniature laptops, Café Lalten is just the sort of place you want to bum around at, while it rains relentlessly outside - KC

content.description: Almost everything about Ye Ole Watering Hole is homely. The space looks like somebody’s cheery living room. Free munchies include sticks of carrots and cucumbers with chaat masala, and masala peanuts. Even the French fries are short, stubby golden fingers, much like the ones mummy made on days that we’d been especially good (or as we now realise, when she was too lazy to care). It has that comfortable vibe of a place where you can make conversation if you want. But staring blankly at the TV is perfectly fine too - NS

Most bars in Colaba are overrun with grimy tourists and for a local to be seen there is a matter of shame. Mondy’s is that rare bar that is as popular with the natives as it is with gap-year Brits. With its high ceilings, tables crammed together and Mario Miranda murals, it’s easy to see why the legend of Mondy’s runs deep - Leo Mirani

The 85-year-old Café Universal is an excellent example of how to renovate an old bar without losing any character. It’s big and bright, with lots of natural light streaming in and the design is very Art Noveau. Universal serves beer and wine at affordable rates and is the sort of place that is really far more pleasant for a few afternoon beers than an evening of heavy drinking - LM

content.description: Leo’s Square is the sort of place one might consider visiting even if you didn’t want a drink. It isn’t nearly as cramped as the original. The wooden café-like tables are spread across the bar area so getting up doesn’t involve making people from the next table shuffle around. The décor is nice, the vibe is friendly and the service is a lot less stuck up than at its older counterpart. But as we savoured Leo’s chicken chilli and hummed to their playlist of classics, we couldn’t help but feel something was amiss. That’s when it hit us. There wasn’t a single tourist in the place. It’s a Leo’s for the locals. Who would have thought? NS

content.description: As far as getting the look right goes, Polly’s wins the disco décor duel hands down. From the daisies in the logo to the bartender’s polka dot shirts, it’s got enough flower power to make you feel groovy baby, yeah. So what if most of the Colaba kids who inhabit the space weren’t born when the classic pop and rock played here was recorded? - KF

content.description: SanQi is like having a drink in a glass house. The walls of the hotel are glass, the walls inside the club are glass and the main bar-area is encased in a glass box surrounded by ceiling-high racks of empty wine bottles. Certainly not the kind of place for a rowdy night-out, but then again, this is the Four Seasons. Transparency issues apart, SanQi has a somewhat limited drinks menu for the bar nights but that also means that a martini costs Rs 450 as opposed to double on any other night. But we get the feeling its late-night licence, will have the place packed like a can of very expensive sardines. Especially since Aer’s shut shop for the monsoons - NS

content.description: Located inside Good Earth, The Tasting Room has managed to do away with the froufrou vibe that characterised it early on and yet retain the touch of sophistication that sets it apart from other bars in the mill area. The wine list is expansive but not necessarily expensive. The Tasting Room isn’t the sort of place you go for a piss-up nor an after-work drink. It is the sort of place that has the power to make you forget about the noise and grime outside and remind you of the joys of just sitting around with a nice drink and a good meal - LM

content.description: Even if some punters find the food at Tote affected and overpriced, they will find that the bar is hardly an also-ran. The cocktails are only Rs 385 each, even the signature horseracing-themed concoctions such as Tote’s Quinella (with vodka, blueberry and smoked rosemary). So for a starting gate, Tote is good enough to get blinkered at. An evening can go something like this: meet up with a friend at the stunning wood-panelled bar; get impressive service even on a busy night; have a couple of drinks; then deduct a couple of grand from your wallet. Our only complaint is that once crowded, the bar loses all of its romance and feels a bit like an Andheri local - Roshni Bajaj Sanghvi

content.description: There’s nothing extreme about the place, unless you think a flatscreen TV on each wall is over-the-top. However, consider that Xtreme Sports Bar is located in the staid and pin-striped neighbourhood of DN Road’s banks and the extreme-ness starts to make sense. For all the bankers and executives in the neighbourhood, here is a nice and noisy after-work option right at their doorsteps. The mezzanine floor has a foosball table on which you can whack foosmen around for Rs 50 an hour. If you prefer to make more calculated shots, the first floor has a pool table for Rs 200 an hour. The xtremely typical retro playlist features songs like Lipps Inc’s “Funky Town”, Laura Branigan’s “Self Control” and Haddaway’s “What is Love” but that’s perfectly fine because the affordable prices, big screens and sporty ambience are really what this place is all about - Aditya Kundalkar

content.description: Bhogdoi, the canteen at Vashi’s Assam Bhawan, is where Assamese folks in Mumbai go when they crave the taste of home. Housed on the first floor of the Bhawan, the no-fuss canteen welcomes lodgers, office babus and engineering students who swear by their thalis. It’s as simple as a set meal can get: roti, rice, dal, two types of vegetables and chicken or fried fish. But it’s all cooked Assamese style by Assamese cooks, which explains why it’s so popular. The vegetable dishes change every day but cover state favourites like kosu xaakor jalukia (colocasia leaves curry), pitika (eggplant and potato mash) and ol kobir bhaji (turnip). Waiters rush in and out of the kitchens during busy lunch hours with thalis filled with deep-fried hilsa and rahu fish, cajoling you to try some more. Keep them coming, we say.

content.description: Flavors is a multi-cuisine hot-spot for Sanpada residents when they want some Italian pizzas along with their crispy chilli chicken. The interiors are bright in hues of sea blue, with fish tanks lining the restaurant’s walls continuing the aquatic theme. The restaurant has a bar-on-wheels, essentially a display trolley of all their liquor bottles, which makes its way through the tables, while the server cheekily asks, “Do you want to get high?” The portions are more than generous. Don’t be surprised to find more chicken in your risotto than the rice, which is Indian unpolished short grain rather than Italian Arborio.

content.description: Real estate is where Navi Mumbai scores over SoBo. Restaurants are two-storied. Nobody is scrimping on portion sizes to pay the high rent, so your plump dim sum can actually come generously over-stuffed with juicy chicken. Golden Wok is all of that. The menu has several pages dedicated to fish, prawns, squid, lamb, chicken and a largish vegetarian selection. This was one of the first speciality Chinese restaurants in Sanpada, and even though mall-central Vashi is just a five-minute drive away, regulars often find their way back for the Golden Wok special soup loaded with fish, prawns, crab, tofu and mushrooms. Families out for their weekend meal just can’t seem to get enough of their burnt garlic rice, prawns in orange sauce and crispy thread chicken.

Notes of Hindustani classical music chase whiffs of fried bombil around Malvan Katta’s old-world interiors. Glass lamps above every table ensure that illumination is pleasantly mellow while brass fans whirr along its walls. It’s the sort of place that demands whispered conversation not because the ambience is formal but because it’s so peaceful. Malwan Katta serves food from the Konkan region. After the pale and perfectly spiced sol kadi has cleansed your palate, fire it up with their meatier offerings. The thali includes two types of vegetable and fish, mutton or chicken, a simple dal, chapattis, rice and a sweet dish. Like most other places in Navi Mumbai, they also serve North Indian and Chinese food but everybody’s clearly there for the catch of the day. There’s even a glass tank outside where you can pick a monster crab and then sip on a beer or two until it gets a complete makeover. When it does eventually arrive at your table, a violent red dressed-up version of what it was, put cutlery aside and dig in. The waiter will all but insist you use your hands – which is the only way you should eat anyway.

Nakshatra, the Indian restaurant at Vashi’s Fortune Select Hotel, is aiming to be Navi Mumbai’s answer to Bukhara, which it well might be, considering that Fortune is the mid-range arm of the ITC group. At Nakshatra you’re more likely to see the satellite city’s corporate bigwigs impressing clients over dinner than families sharing a jhinga malaikari. Wine glasses are clinked as business deals are clinched over chunks of rara gosht and a bowlful of the dal nakshatra tempered on the dal-tadka trolley by your table. Don’t leave without trying the nashile jamun: the glistening balls of gulab jamun are dunked in sugar syrup and then flambéed for visual appeal. However we didnt have the courage to try and find out what a Parsi-style patra ni machi was doing on an North Indian menu.

content.description: Pot Pourri in Vashi’s Inorbit mall has the laid-back air of a place that works just as well for a quick meal as it does for a couple of after-work pints. There’s cherry-red diner-style seating, the walls are filled with frames of random prints that range from vintage designs and trippy Goa babas to Gwen Stefani lips and the music is mostly retro. At lunch, Pot Pourri isn’t too full except for a few people digging into their Rs 299 buffet. But come sundown, the smattering of couples gives way to larger and significantly louder groups guzzling beer and munching on slices of four-cheese pizza. The music gets louder, soft conversation is replaced by animated discussions and the otherwise-quiet restaurant turns into an all-out pub.

content.description: Doesn’t sound right, does it? We didn’t think so either, so we asked the owners of Rude Lounge about their mission statement: service with a snarl. “We thought people would love to see waiters – who are supposed to be courteous, saying ‘yes ma’am, no ma’am, thank you sir’ – talk rudely to customers or dump the order on the table,” said Harpreet Singh, the owner. “The idea was to do something different.” That was in December 2008, when the CBD Belapur themed bar first opened. Fortunately, we didn’t see much of this intent to serve badly. What we did find was some very happy Happy hours. At the Rude Lounge, ladies get two pegs of vodka or beer on the house on Mondays and unlimited alcohol on Wednesday, and everybody gets one-on-one on beer on Tuesdays and Thursdays. The crowd is as much of a mixed bag as the playlist, the food and cocktails aren’t half bad and the décor is a few notches above a neighbourhood bar. It’s actually quite nice but don’t tell them that.

content.description: Who would’ve thought that one of the hotels along the Mumbai-Pune expressway housed a Kashmiri shikara-themed restaurant? Shikara has all the jazz of ghazal singers, dining in house-boats on a pond and waddling geese. The moment you enter you’re taken aback by the sheer size of the boats and the open air roof (there’s a mock ceiling for the monsoon) under which sit ghazal singers, magicians, astrologers, mehndiwalas and choodiwalas. There are three different kinds of seating arrangements: a shikara or houseboat (including an air-conditioned one), traditional baithaks and regular sofas, for those who would rather just skip the shenanigans and focus on the food. Though they have a variety of Indian and Chinese dishes, we recommend sticking to the Kashmiri fare like chicken yakhni, paneer gulnar, goshtaba and rogan gosht.

If their two-page menu solely dedicated to crab and lobster is anything to go by, there’s definitely something fishy going on here. The great thing about this seafood restaurant in Vashi’s Tunga Reganza Hotel is that they aren’t restricted to a particular cuisine. You could have a Vietnamese bassa steamed with ginger, onion and scallion, a grilled South American hake fish, Kottayam fish curry or a kombdi malvani masala, all in the same meal. Vegetarians here have it good as well. There’s Rajasthani Bhindi, golden fried babycorn in sweet and spicy sauce, miloni subzi (vegetable curry) and pan-fried Chinese greens in butter and garlic; so much more than the butter-paneer options that vegetarians are slowly starting to detest.

If the shops on a year-round sale at Raghuleela Mall aren’t enough to make you get up and take notice, their dining options certainly will. Qzeenz, the food court, has Ho Ho Stix for Chinese, Alibaba 40 Zaike for Indian, Jamba Juice and a village-themed restaurant for all things Indian. There’s not a McDonalds or a Pizza Hut in sight, so put your burger cravings on hold and try some bhakris on a charpai over a cool mud floor instead. The Village tries to recreate the charm of a rustic village setting within the confines of the concrete jungle. There are mud plastered walls, live folk dances and a tree sheltering an astrologer, a bangle maker and a potter. The food covers the cuisines of Gujarat, Rajasthan, Punjab and south India, so you can dig into chole, kachori, daal baati churma, dosa and aloo chaat.

content.description: To hear Mocambo’s manager Bennil D’Mello tell it, it doesn’t take much to prepare the city’s biggest portion of pork chops. “We marinate them in HP Sauce, olive oil and ground pepper for about a day, hammer them with a steak hammer to tenderise them and then char grill them for 25 minutes,” said the ever-smiling D’Mello. The result, though, is pure piggy heaven.Each order of pork chops brings you two enormous hunks of meat glistening on the bone – more than half a kilo of carnivorous pleasure. They simper on a steaming platter with a simple accompaniment of mashed potatoes and crisp vegetables. “People come from all over Bombay to eat them,” said D’Mello.Just as gigantic but far more complex are Tote’s chops, a kilo-and-a-half of pork that serves four. The marinade for the Tote chops includes ginger-garlic paste, kasoori methi and nutmeg and they’re served with a dollop of apple butter, with corn muffins. There’s also a sauce involving white wine, pork sausages, celery and pureed mango achaar. Now that’s gourmet food for gourmands.

"If it’s an all-nighter you’re trying to pull, we suggest you follow the smell of coffee beans to Costa Coffee. The UK-based coffee chain can pour a coffee of your choice into a 600ml cup. It’s more of a soup bowl than a mug of coffee but it’s guaranteed to keep you up till the wee hours of the morning."

content.description: Morsels of kebabs can be disappointing because they are just that, mere morsels. Barely have we begun to relish the flavour of the tender meat and they’re gone. But not if you’re eating Kareem’s shikampuris. Foodies have come up with several versions of the shikampuri. In one, a filling of yoghurt, mint and onion is added to the core of the kebab. Another variant has a filling of boiled egg. Our favourite, however, is Kareem’s. To create every succulent shikampuri, a full 100 grams of mince is cooked with gram flour paste, garlic, chilli powder, garam masala and whole spices. The chef coats the kebab with a layer of fried egg to hold it together. When the shikampuri arrives at your table, you know it’s a kebab that brings more than enough meat to your meal.

content.description: Golden Star Thali is where bottomless stomachs meet their match in endless servings of festive food from Gujarat and Rajasthan.The shiny brass thalis (already bigger than any dinner plate you might own) hold freshly prepared lunches and dinners that typically include the following: one chaat, one fried farsan, one steamed farsan, one paneer vegetable, one green vegetable, one potato-based vegetable, one lentil-based vegetable, a Gujarati sweet dal, a dal bati with choorma, a dahi kadhi, ghee-drizzled phulkas, biscuit bhakris, aloo parathas, masala puris, bajra or jowar rotlas, steamed rice, masala khichdi and pulao.This is in addition to what’s already on the plate before the food arrives – green chutney, garlic chutney, sweet-sour chutney, a masala-stuffed chilli, mango pickle, papads, sago chips, potato wafers, cucumber relish, raita and curd – and what is around the plate: smoked masala chaas and a bottle of mineral water. Don’t leave. We’re not finished yet. Desserts between Monday and Saturday include unlimited helpings of two sweets, one of which is usually basundi, Rajasthani kheer, fruit salad, shrikhand or gulab jamun, the other desi ghee jalebi, saffron puranpoli or malpua rabdi.On Sundays, we recommend wearing drawstring pants because they serve three sweets, which could be anything from malai cham cham, badam bhog, kesar toast, mevadi kheer, strawberry basundi, mohan thal or ras malai. In the summer, a season when you’ll need drawstrings and reservations, there’s also unlimited aam ras.

content.description: If you’re passing by, Mehraj Bhai, from the Meerut branch of yakhni pulao makers, makes sure you get a whiff of his pulao, simmering in massive handis. We got a free taste and just had to have some more. Their fragrant chicken and mutton pulaos are as tasty as their red and orange coloured zarda rice with bits of tutti-frutti. You could mix it up with the pulao or parcel it along with some dal gosht.

The restaurant Global Fusion exists to bust two major myths concerning Japan’s most popular contribution to the world’s culinary culture. One, sushi must be expensive and two, there are no respectable vegetarian versions of sushi. Standing before the awesome spread at the Khar eatery, the phrase “teri maki” need not be either an abuse or an envious exclamation because not only is there an endless supply of different kinds of maki, but there’s also sashimi and other kinds of sushi.Global Fusion serves up 20 kinds of sushi and sashimi to its customers. Here’s what makes all this particularly euphoria-inducing: it’s cheap. For your money, you get unlimited sushi and you can also wolf down a range of delicious Chinese starters, soups as well as a buffet spread of forgettable main courses and desserts. We’d advise you to stick to the sushi spread. Prawns, avocado, tuna, octopus, cucumber – it’s all there on a platter, waiting to be gobbled up. The chefs keep rolling the goods out so every time a platter looks empty-ish, a new batch arrives. It may not meet Chef Morimoto’s exacting standards but the sushi is perfectly respectable, whether it has raw fish in it or cucumber, and the range Global Fusion offers is impressive. If they’d had a branch in Middle Earth, then the raw-fish loving Gollum would never have left the building.
